New research published Wednesday revealed that the vast majority, as much as 90 percent, US deaths from the coronavirus outbreak could have been avoided if strict social distancing measures were imposed just two weeks earlier.
After the social distancing order, the number of deaths began to rise rapidly across the country, now topping 26,000 just a month later.
Pull Quote Eight Republican governors still have not issued statewide stay-at-home orders as deaths in the U.S. top 26,000.
Kentucky's social distancing measure was issued March 26; Tennessee waited until the last minute of March 31.
"Decisions about the timing of imposing social distancing are now largely behind us," wrote Jewell and Jewell.